Poland and space.
Last week, at the Ministerial Meeting of the European Space Agency, Poland was adopted by the twentieth member of the European Space Agency as the second country from the former Eastern bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of ESA on 12 September 2008).
Poland had begun close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and had actively participated in a number of Agency projects in the following years.
But Poland's way to space started a lot earlier.
Even before the Second World War, Polish enthusiasts had been travelling to space, but that was not always the case.
I recall, for example, a lecture by A. Sternfeld, who presented ideas at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory on 6 December 1933 from his pioneering work "Introduction to Space."
The ideas of the young engineer (1905) left the audience indifferent, and after a few years Sternfeld remembered that it was only Dr. Jan Gadomsky who was interested in his work.
In 1934, in France, Sternfeld won the Robert Esno-Peltry and André Luis Hirsch award for "Introduction to Space."
Dr. Jan Gadomsky (1899 - 1966), mentioned above, later became a great promoter of astronomy and space science.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish magazines and wrote a series of books on these sciences.
Gadomsky became a world space propaganda player, and his contribution was appreciated, including the fact that one of the craters on the back of the Moon was named after him.
As early as 1925, Poland had built a rail-drive with a missile engine.
Unfortunately, the author of the idea remained unknown, as did the details of the project.
It is not even clear whether a rocket was to be used to break the cart or to stop it.
Information about this is only available from the press of that era.
From 1933 the Polish artillery began to think of rockets.
The study was carried out by the Arms Technology Section, in cooperation with professors Mojitski and Boulevard Wolfke.
The remaining material shows that the studies have reached the stage of practical testing.
But with the coming of the German troops, the work was interrupted.
In 1937, the Specialized Press introduced the idea of a photovoltaic fighter rocket proposed by the engineer of Rogozinski, and the following year the work of the author's “air torpedo and bomb-aircraft missile” was launched by Lelivi-Kivoblotski.
Both projects have been developed for the military use of missile engines.
Prior to the war, the Interim Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy), which coordinated all the work, was involved in all military missile applications.
The committee was established in 1937, but after two years of operation, the work ended as a result of the outbreak of the war.
The next space science work appeared in the Polish press after the war, thanks to the work of the Polish Society of Astronautics (Polskie Towerzystwo Astronomyczne).
For the first time, there is a mention of society in the November 1954 issue of the magazine “Problems”, which publishes four voluminous articles on space science.
In one of them, Professor M. Subotovich offered to organize a space society.
At that time, artificial satellite projects had been gaining momentum, and it was clear that space exploration was a promising industry.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Society of Astronautics (PAA) has tried to join the International Federation of Astronautics (founded in 1951), and it has become a valid member in the fall.
And the following year, the first president of the PAA, Kazimez Zarankewicz (1902-1959) became the vice-president of the International Federation of Astronautics.
He remained in office until his death in 1959.
Since 1956 the PAA has made a significant contribution to the development of the very successful Meteorological Missile RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which was the first Polish missile to carry out scientific research.
The first type of RM-1 was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
The rocket, which was able to cross a distance of 1,800 m, was about 80 cm long and weighed less than 5 kg.
Subsequently, an improved version of RM-1A was built, and in the summer of 1959 a two-stage RM-2 missile was tested on the Bledovsk Desert.
The rocket was about 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
The next version of the missile was already in a position to do real scientific work - the RM-34 missile could have crossed 14.5 km, and its mission was to observe the high wind.
But in 1962, further development was halted.
The origin of the first RM-type rockets was a meteor-1 missile developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed to be two-stage, with a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types (specified as meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) have been developed, which differ in size for scientific equipment.
Meteorological 1A had a space of 0.4 litre, Meteorological 1B 0.34 litre and Meteorological 1C 0.62l.
The maximum range for all three types of flight was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, a meteor-2 missile was being developed at the Aviation Institute, and its first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 missile, with a 380 kg start-up weight, was able to produce a useful load of 10 kg to a height of about 60 km.
==History==The versions of Meteorological-2N and Meteorological-3 were then built.
It is also worth mentioning Poland's accession to COSPAR (Space Research Committee) in 1960 and the establishment of the COSPAR National Committee two years later.
In addition, under the Intercosmos programme, Poland participated in space exploration on Soviet artificial satellites, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslav Hermashzewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
