Sabo: "The Germans have a more important role to play."
Germany abstained in the vote on the recognition of Palestine.
In the view of Stephen Sabo, the US-Europe liaison expert, in doing so, Berlin is on a narrow diplomatic track.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany first indicated that it would vote against the Palestinian application for observer status with the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained in the vote.
Why?
Stephen Sabo: Germany does not support Israeli actions in Gaza.
Germany must now be careful about its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I believe that it also does not support the American position.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence, without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained in the vote on the imposition of a no-flight zone.
In the end, NATO made this offer.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on complex international issues?
Yes, it is.
The fact is that it is in the process of transforming its foreign policy, that is, moving from the policy that the US was, so to speak, to the very German foreign policy.
The situation is further complicated by the fact that Europeans do not have a coherent common policy.
So the Germans are back between the two fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not accustomed to it.
I think they're only getting a sense of their role for now, but they're on the way to “more normal” foreign policy.
A foreign policy like that of France or the United Kingdom.
What exactly does “normal” foreign policy mean from a German point of view?
It is a willingness to take a national stand independent of the position of the US or European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy depends on economic policy, that is, exports and links to certain regions, such as Russia, China, or the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests are very different from those of other major States, and Germany must therefore defend its interests.
Did those economic interests affect the position in the Middle East conflict and the vote in the United Nations?
First, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, particularly in the Gulf States.
It must therefore be careful not to offend the public and elite in the Arab countries.
Either way, it plays a role.
But I wouldn't give it too much meaning, it's not a complete one-sided connection.
But in any case, it plays an important role in the calculation of the Germans.
Did Germany harm its relationship with the US by refraining from making important decisions, such as the Palestinian vote?
I am sure that in Europe, and even in the US, there is a prevailing understanding of the German position.
So I don't think it was as dramatic as it was in the Libyan question.
Germany may even gain some respect in this way.
It is a signal that it should be taken seriously as a player in the international arena and that its interests should be taken into account.
There are different views in Europe on the Palestinian initiative.
On the contrary, the US has made clear its support for the veto.
Is there a divergence of views between the US and many European States?
Because of American domestic policy, such differences have always existed.
I believe that Obama’s government, deep down, has a sufficient understanding of the European position.
But in view of the local political situation, the Government, of course, cannot take that position openly.
I believe that significant differences of opinion are not as significant as they always seem.
If you consider the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, you will notice that Obama is not at all thrilled by Netanyahu’s policy.
Is it easy for Germany to combine its close links with Israel and the US on the one hand and the position of the EU's most important partner on the other?
I think that's what makes the situation so difficult for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a bit easier for the Germans to have a single, uncontroversial European policy, but it is not.
Therefore, they cannot take a broader approach and must instead act on the basis of their own vision.
That's what they do with the euro.
I think that in the future Germany will take the lead in developing a common European position.
It is clear that this is not easy for Germany, at least because of its links with Israel.
It's always been a delicate subject.
But I think it's clear to the Germans that they have to play a more independent role.
If Germany sees itself as an important international player, will it really take the lead?
Or is Germany still hard to lead?
Germany is not accustomed to it, it is still always uncomfortable, and, for obvious reasons, it is always hard to play a significant role.
Consider, for example, the euro crisis - every time Germany assumes an important role, a wide range of anti-German sentiments manifest themselves.
It's not easy for the Germans to deal with.
In fact, it's an old problem: you don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more difficult situation than the US.
It must take into account a wide range of neighbours and views, which is not easy.
So, the US's influence in European politics is constantly weakening, but at the moment the EU is not filling this vacuum, so who is left?
The Germans will just have to play a bigger role.
Even if you don't like it, that's the way life is.
Stephen Sabo is the Deputy Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, D.C., an institution in which academics and political experts from Europe and North America are jointly studying the problems of the Transatlantic Community.
In addition, Sabo is a member of the German Marshall Foundation, in which he specializes in German politics, U.S. foreign policy, and trans-Atlantic links.
