Bradley Manning didn't complain of ill-treatment, claims the charge.
The prosecution is trying to disprove Bradley Manning's allegations of poor conditions of detention.
The hearing focused on Manning's stay in the military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defence requires that the case be closed on the ground that Manning's conditions of detention were brutal.
The U.S. Army is accused of abducting several thousand secret documents.
On Friday, the prosecution tried to prove that Private Bradley Manning, who had been accused of the largest leak of classified material in United States history, had not availed himself of many opportunities to file a complaint of ill-treatment, which he said he had had to endure while in a military prison.
During cross-examination at a pre-trial hearing in Fort Mid, Maryland, the Military Prosecutor, Major Ashden Fain, stated that the records of the weekly visits to Manning by the prison authorities in nine months of his detention in Quantico, Virginia, did not contain any complaints of ill-treatment.
The cross-examination of the defence motion to discontinue the Manning case, on the basis that the conditions of his detention were cruel and in themselves a sufficient penalty, was conducted the day after Manning stated that he had intended to commit suicide while in detention.
A military intelligence analyst, who was arrested in June 2010, is charged with theft of several thousand secret documents during his service in Iraq.
The material was later published on the WikiLeaks web site.
WikiLeaks did not confirm that Manning was the source of the information.
During the Friday's hearing, Prosecutor Fain, along with Manning, reviewed the reports that had been completed following the visits to Manning by the Administration during his stay at Quantico prison, where he was held under strict conditions of detention from July 2010 to April 2011.
During the visits, the prison officials asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When D.A. Feyn asked about the reports on Friday, Manning admitted that he considered the treatment of himself by the prison administration to be “excellent” and the general conditions of detention to be “very professionally organized”.
The reports reviewed do not contain complaints of ill-treatment, despite the fact that Manning was explicitly asked about the conditions of his detention, Phein argues.
Manning replied that he had expressed his oral concern about the problems and that the officials who had visited had discussed the problems with him and had stated that they would deal with them, but had not recorded them in writing.
"They recorded "no problems" (after discussing my complaints), but that doesn't mean I didn't raise the subject," Manning says.
The Military Judge, Colonel Denise Lindh, also asked Manning why he had not complained of ill-treatment in January 2011 during a meeting of a committee that had been considering suicidal intent, which he had expressed in writing a few months earlier.
Manning replied that during that session he wanted to be removed from the “injury warning” regime and eased the conditions of detention.
The military authorities explained that the limited regime of detention, at a level lower than the surveillance regime for the prevention of suicide, had been put in place to protect the prisoner, as well as for the safety of others.
"I wanted to let the administration know that I'm okay with them to end the injury-prevention regime... so that my standard of living would improve, in my view," Manning explained.
On Thursday, Manning witnessed his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for almost two months before being transferred to a prison at a naval base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He reported that he had thought of suicide in Kuwait, and that he had lost consciousness once because of the heat.
He explained that it is very psychologically difficult when you are not allowed to know how your fate is handled and what is happening in the outside world.
"My world has succumbed to Camp Arifjan's base, to the size of my prison," said Manning on Thursday.
- I thought I was gonna die in that cage."
While in Quantico, Manning, he said, spent most of his time in a small cell - at least 21 hours, and often more than 23 hours a day - all alone.
Manning reports that he was allowed to keep only the mattress, the blanket, the slippers, a number of items of clothing, and the glasses.
He says he was trying to move, because sleep, or even just lie down during the daytime, was forbidden by the rules.
According to Manning, during his sleep, he was constantly hit by a light coming out of the cell.
If the guards did not see his face when he was turning around in bed at night, he said he was waken up and forced to turn on his back.
Manning's lawyer filed a formal objection to the ill-treatment of Manning in January 2011.
In April 2011, Manning was transferred to a military prison in Fort Leavenworth, Kansas.
In addition, on Friday, the judge interrogated Manning about the statement he made during his statement on Thursday that, after he had been forced to sleep naked in his cell in Quantico one night, he had been forced to stand naked in front of the security guards and other prisoners for a morning check.
Manning stated that he had not been able to cover himself with a blanket at the time of the check.
In answer to the judge's questions on Friday, Manning said that he had learned from the guard's order that he should drop a blanket to cover for, but admitted that no one had direct orders him to dump him.
On Thursday, Manning said that he had been forced to sleep naked last night because of his attempt to show the officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning said he told the officer that he could use a pair of underpants or slippers to hurt himself, but he didn't do it.
That night, according to Manning's statement, his underwear, his slippers, and his glasses were taken out of his cell.
His lawyers hoped that the judge would at least take into account what he had to endure during his detention and significantly shorten the sentence if Manning was found guilty by the military court, which was to start his trial early next year.
The defence stated that it was planning to invite Manning to plead guilty to less serious crimes, while the other charges would be challenged as excessive.
The resumption of the hearing is scheduled this weekend, and the prosecution is expected to insist that the conditions of detention have been justified.
The Pentagon claims that Manning was held in Quantico in accordance with the rules governing the detention of persons under the strictest possible regime.
Among the charges brought against Manning are abetting an adversary, illegal promotion of data on the Internet, the transmission of information relating to national defence, and the theft of State property or documents.
If he is convicted of all counts of the indictment, he may be sentenced to life imprisonment.
