Old battles in the new Middle East
A ceasefire agreement between Israel and the Hamas faction can provide a fragile foundation for further peace
Can there be lasting peace between Arabs and Israelis in the Middle East?
Another round of bloodshed leads to the conclusion that such hopes are futile.
It is a common, pointless debate about who started the first time; a large number of buildings have become ruins; more than 140 Palestinians, the majority of whom were civilians, and six Israelis have been killed; and, for the first time in the conflict, rockets fired from the Gaza Strip landed in the vicinity of the capital of Israel, Tel-Aviv, and the holy city of Jerusalem.
However, despite the hopeless links between Israelis and Palestinians in their perpetual conflict, the Middle East has undergone a change.
This may not be the case, but the events of the “Arab Spring” have converged in a rebel storm with many well-established realities, and the Palestinians and the Israelis have not been able to stay away from the storm that shakes the region.
Perhaps as a result, their struggle will become even more bloody than before.
There are, however, reasons for hope of overcoming this fatal impasse.
A War Without Winners
At first glance, the situation is not a cause for optimism.
Even if the cease-fire, which was signed on 21 November, is being implemented, the fighting this week has only reinforced the positions of the militants on both sides.
The leaders of the Hamas Islamist movement, which had come to power in the Gaza Strip in 2007, will claim to have forced Israel to withdraw despite the losses they had suffered.
Despite the fact that some leaders of the faction have been destroyed and 1.7 million people have been blocked in one of the most densely populated and troubled parts of the world, Israel has failed to destroy Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is increasing its popularity in the West Bank, another Palestinian territory currently controlled by the more moderate Fatah movement.
Moreover, the leaders of Hamas may well conclude that time works for them.
As the influence of Islamist movements grows in the Arab world, Hamas is developing new powerful and rich friends.
The renaissance of the regional leader of Turkey, who was once the closest ally of Israel among the Muslim countries, has been supporting Hamas; her example has been followed by Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamic States in the Persian Gulf.
Hamas's ceremonial supporters claim the establishment of an Islamist half-month around Israel, from Lebanon to the north, which is ruled by the Hezbollah militant group, to Syria, where the increasingly pro-Islamic rebels are about to overthrow Bashar Assad's power, and further to Jordan, where the King's authorities threaten Hamas allies.
The most significant change in the balance of power in the region occurred on the southern borders of Israel, in the most populous and important Arab country, Egypt, where the influence of the Muslim Brotherhood was strengthened under President Mohammed Morsi.
Hosni Mubarak, who had ruled Egypt for 30 years and had been overthrown in 2011, was a secular dictator who did not pay much attention to the support of Hamas.
By contrast, the Muslim brothers are an organization that is much like Hamas, and their leaders are more prone to populism.
In future diplomatic positions, Hamas can become a significant player whose voice will not be silenced even by Israel and America.
At the same time, the “hard” line in Israel will come to the opposite conclusion.
In a military sense, Hamas was defeated.
Israel's Iron Dome missile system had justified the cost of its establishment and had successfully destroyed many of the rockets launched by Hamas.
Israelis can sleep quietly, at least for a while.
As far as diplomacy is concerned, the US has remained steadfast; many European countries have also blamed Hamas for launching the last round of violence.
Another important factor is the economic prosperity of Israel, particularly under the Government of Binyamin Netanyahu, which has largely ignored the peace process.
Despite the fact that some 30 Israelis had been killed by rockets fired from the Gaza Strip since 2004, Israel had been able to minimize the problem of suicide bombers, in part through the wall that entered the West Bank of the Jordan, a significant part of the unrecognized Palestinian State, and to protect Jewish settlements, which continued to expand despite the illegality of such actions under international law.
The position of Prime Minister Netanyahu, whose Likud party, in preparation for the elections scheduled for 22 January, has joined with even more aggressive conservatives under the leadership of Avigdor Lieberman, is very convenient.
What is the point of condoning the Palestinians and giving them their own State?
If they hand over all the authority in the West Bank, would they not start launching rockets from there towards Israel, as did their fellow people in the Gaza Strip?
It's best to keep them out of the wall and stifle any attempt to lift their heads.
Proponents of the hard line may win; however, their calculations may be rebutted in the Arab spring.
While Islamists who come to power in Egypt and in other countries are not very fond of Israel, their priority will be internal problems.
Israel's defence budget is larger than all of its Arab neighbours combined.
The outbreak of war with the regional super-Power is unlikely to help Arab Governments to strengthen their economies.
The pragmatism of the president of Egypt, Mursi, who worked with Barack Obama to work on a ceasefire is a good sign and can mark the beginning of a change.
Israel, to the same extent, must bear in mind the long-term consequences of its policies.
As the democratic changes in the Arab countries take place, depriving the Palestinians of the right to self-determination is a time bomb that will explode sooner or later in the occupied territories of Israel, like the bus that exploded in Tel-Aviv this week.
Repressions are already undermining the foundations of the democratic order in the Jewish State, and the demographic dimension, the growth of the Arab population, is only exacerbating those problems.
The bloodthirsty operations that take place every few years in the Gaza Strip to suppress the Hamas movement have to pay for the growing discontent of the international community.
Both sides need external impulse
There remains the only solution that is unrelentingly called for by sound representatives on both sides, as well as most of the rest of the world and our newspaper: the formation of two States and Israel's concessions to territories in exchange for security.
The hope remains, not too strong in the short term, that a cease-fire will enable other countries to have a more effective impact on the parties to the conflict.
Egypt, which is long overdue in its decision to block the flow of arms to the Gaza Strip, as well as Turkey and Qatar, has a more advantageous position than ever to persuade Hamas to accept the boundaries of the Jewish State adopted since 1967, taking into account the exchange of territories and the shared use of Jerusalem.
Other Arab countries must also make efforts to reconcile the Hamas and Fatah movements.
This would do more to create a Palestinian State than the upcoming United Nations vote, which could result in the recognition of the virtual statehood of Palestine.
President Obama has a role to play in bringing Israel to the negotiating table.
During his first term, he never presented his own peace plan.
Upon his return to the White House, he continued to show a reluctance to engage in the solution of the problem.
This is a catastrophic short-sighted position.
The United States is vitally interested in stability in the Middle East.
This is possible only in the case of a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
The Unified Packing for Cigarette Act has entered into force in Australia.
Warnings about the harm of smoking and the images of disease-affected body parts are contrasted on depressing green boxes that are the same for all cigarette stamps.
Australia's first single-packing of cigarettes and tobacco has come into force in global practice, replacing logos and colored stamps with a box of depressing olives with depressing images of sick body parts and images of children whose health is affected by the smoking of their parents.
In addition to the different images and inscriptions that warn of the harm of smoking, the only difference between packets that are mandatory from this Saturday is the name of the stamps, which are printed in the same small font.
These are the most stringent conditions in the world for the packaging of tobacco.
The Federal Government of Australia states that the aim of this measure is to keep young people from smoking, depriving them of this harmful fashion habit.
This decision was based on studies that showed that people who had not started smoking under 26 years of age had never become smokers in 99 out of 100 cases.
“It is evident that even at the youngest age, children understand the meaning that tobacco companies are trying to convey through packaging,” explains the Minister of Health, Tanya Plybersek, referring to studies that have shown that, for example, the crown in the logo is associated with the idea of a princess.
Australia is one of the countries with the world's lowest smoking rate, so that these changes will not have a significant impact on the profit of transnational corporations, but other countries are already considering such measures.
Members of the tobacco industry have strongly opposed the adoption of the Act.
Tobacco companies claim that this will only increase the share of the black market in which cheap and affordable cigarettes will be sold.
"This law will have serious consequences, different from the ones that their initiators thought it might have," Scott McIntyre, a British American Tobacco agent in Australia.
Forged producers from China and Indonesia will deliver far more of these products for sale on the streets of Australia.
For some, on the other hand, new laws promote business growth.
Sandra Ha, from a small family company, Zico Import Pty Ltd., claims that the demand for cigarettes and silicon casings concealing unpleasant images on the package has grown rapidly (practicably from zero) since two months ago, companies such as British American Tobacco, British Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris, and Japan Tobacco lost the case in Australia's High Court, where they tried to appeal the law.
According to Sandra Ha, Zico has already sold about 6,000 items to the wholesalers and is waiting for a new shipment.
It's a good business for us.
In the view of experts, the popularity of social media among the target population is a potential obstacle to the effectiveness of such measures.
Following the passage of a number of laws in Australia that have made illegal television advertising and support for sporting events, as well as bans on the display of cigarettes, the advertising of tobacco has moved to the Internet.
The Australian Government had banned local companies and websites from posting ads online, but it could not restrict foreign websites.
"If you're selling tobacco and you've only got this little loophole, the idea of moving your product on the Internet is very tempting," explains Becky Freeman, a student of public health at the University of Sydney.
Freeman has noted an increase in the number of brand reviews written on behalf of allegedly common users on social media such as YouTube, Twitter, and Facebook.
