The hardest profession in the world: miners from Kawah Ijena
For four euros, Indonesian miners risk their lives and health by dragging 70 kilos of sulfur to the top of the volcano on the steep rock trails.
There are people for whom their work is hell, and others are literally working in hell.
Among them is Anto Vijaya, one of the 400 miners who make a living by sulfur mining in the volcano Kawah Ijen, located in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
Every day Anto goes down to the bottom of the crater, where the sulfurous gas coming up from the depths of the earth freezes in contact with the air.
He puts the huge pieces of sulfur up to 70 kg in two bamboo baskets, puts the baskets on his shoulders, and carries them up on a rocky road.
Up to the top of a volcano of 2,386 meters, it is only 250 meters high, but it takes the tired porters more than 40 minutes to climb up with a turtle’s step, with difficulty in holding the balance, and by bypassing the road carefully so as not to slip or fall off the cliff.
They know that one wrong move can cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who fell off the rocks of Kawah Ijen a few years ago.
The miners from Kavah Ijen make 5 eurocents for each kilogram of sulphur that they produce.
Upstairs, they set up a road between the tourists who photographed them, as if they were circus monkeys and, when they were tired of the heavy baskets, marched three kilometers to the balance that the mining company had set up a little higher, at a height of 1,850 metres.
This is the PT Candy Ngrimbi, a company that has been operating this volcano since 1960 and, best and best not to say, its employees, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 eurocents) for each kilogram of sulphur.
It then sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 eurocents) of petrochemical production, since it is common in daily life and is used to make matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite, and even to bleach sugar.
"Because the norm is 70 kilos, we make about Rs. 46,000 (Euro3.8) for every walk," explains Anto, who usually carries out three daily shifts.
He spends three hours on each of them, and at the end of the day he feels broken, but they allow him to save Rs. 138,000 (Euro1.5) by the end of the day.
